WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.500 --> 00:00:07.380
Good afternoon, everyone, and welcome to this mini symposium on non-coding

2
00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:11.340
RNA, regulation of cancer hallmarks, therapeutic resistance,

3
00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:15.260
and biomarker discovery. It is really a pleasure

4
00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:19.020
to chair this session and introduce such

5
00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:21.480
an outstanding group of speakers.

6
00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:25.600
I am Emanuela Ferracin. I am a scientist at the University of

7
00:00:25.640 --> 00:00:27.800
Bologna, and I will chair this session.

8
00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:30.680
Want to introduce?

9
00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:35.060
Okay. Over the past decade, non-coding

10
00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:39.120
RNAs have evolved from being considered transcriptional

11
00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:41.820
byproducts to key regulators

12
00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:45.600
of cellular identity and disease.

13
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.960
We now appreciate that diverse classes of non-coding

14
00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:53.760
RNAs play fundamental roles across essentially

15
00:00:53.920 --> 00:00:55.520
all hallmarks of cancer.

16
00:00:56.340 --> 00:00:59.800
And today, we know that these molecules are not only

17
00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:03.980
mechanistic regulators, but they are becoming

18
00:01:04.041 --> 00:01:07.960
increasingly actionable, serving as drivers of tumor

19
00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:11.950
progression, mediators of therapeutic resistance, and

20
00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:15.560
promising biomarkers and therapeutic targets.

21
00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:20.420
Their relevance is demonstrated also by the over 200

22
00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:23.880
posters that are presented this year at the

23
00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:25.100
ACR meeting.

24
00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.380
And this mini symposium brings together a set of

25
00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:33.460
presentations that span the entire spectrum

26
00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:36.920
of non-coding RNA functions and activities.

27
00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:42.340
We will start with Dr. Hung, who will discuss the

28
00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:46.180
regulation of ribosomal RNA synthesis in acute myeloid

29
00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:50.180
leukemia and highlight how increased ribosomal RNA

30
00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:54.080
production represents a therapeutic vulnerability.

31
00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:58.440
Then we will move forward toward other topics

32
00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:02.100
involving the study of how non-coding RNA mediate

33
00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:06.130
radiation resistance in cervical adenocarcinoma by

34
00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:06.940
Mingji Zhu.

35
00:02:08.081 --> 00:02:12.010
And then we will discover with Ahmad Ziyadeh,

36
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.520
innovative targeting strategies for the tumor

37
00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:19.380
microenvironment in renal cell carcinoma.

38
00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:22.540
We will hear from Katie Swankut,

39
00:02:23.430 --> 00:02:27.320
the emerging and fascinating area of mitochondrial transfer

40
00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.040
RNAs and how they modify breast cancer

41
00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:33.720
development and metastasis.

42
00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:39.000
Yori Kohando will take us into the clinical and diagnostic field,

43
00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:42.640
presenting a high compelling study on urinary extracellular

44
00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:45.260
vesicle microRNA profiling.

45
00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:50.060
And Amartya Pal will close the session with an

46
00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:54.000
exciting example of therapeutic innovation, presenting

47
00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:55.820
multimodal microRNA-based

48
00:02:56.680 --> 00:03:00.360
strategy designed to overcome resistance to PARP inhibitors in

49
00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:01.360
ovarian cancer.

50
00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:06.300
Together, all the presentations highlight a central concept,

51
00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:09.560
that non-coding RNA are very relevant

52
00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:13.100
regulatory hubs in cancer, regulating multiple

53
00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:17.090
oncogenic pathways, including metabolism, ribosome

54
00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:20.790
biogenesis, cell survival, and thus offering a

55
00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:24.190
very unique opportunity for therapeutic intervention.

56
00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:28.940
So as you listen, I encourage you to think two

57
00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:32.340
possible question to present to the speaker at the end of each

58
00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:35.140
session, because we will have time for

59
00:03:35.180 --> 00:03:38.620
discussion, and especially to

60
00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:42.780
focus on how we can today try to transfer all

61
00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:46.590
our knowledge on non-coding RNA toward the bedside and

62
00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:50.260
toward discoveries that have a real clinical

63
00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:53.760
impact. So this is my pleasure to introduce

64
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.560
our first speaker, Dr. Hung.

65
00:04:18.921 --> 00:04:22.840
Good afternoon, everyone, and thank you to the organizers for this opportunity.

66
00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:26.280
My name is Putzer Hung, and I'm a postdoctoral fellow in the lab of Dr.

67
00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:29.099
Vikram Palkar at the University of Pennsylvania.

68
00:04:29.140 --> 00:04:32.530
Today, I'll be sharing some of our developing work on the characterization and

69
00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:36.220
targeting of ribosomal RNA synthesis in acute myeloid leukemia,

70
00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:36.780
AML.

71
00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:39.440
I have no financial disclosures.

72
00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:44.270
AML is one of the deadliest blood cancers in adults, with

73
00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:47.430
five-year overall survivals of only 20% to 30%.

74
00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:51.560
Relapse and therapy resistance are common, while second-line treatment options

75
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:54.820
remain limited, underscoring a major unmet clinical need.

76
00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.020
A defining morphologic feature of AML cells is the presence

77
00:04:59.120 --> 00:05:02.780
of enlarged nucleoli, shown here by the red

78
00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:06.380
arrows, which are sites of ribosomal RNA or rRNA

79
00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:07.040
synthesis.

80
00:05:08.560 --> 00:05:12.280
rRNA are specialized non-coding RNAs that form the catalytic

81
00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:16.240
cores of ribosomes. As you can see in this cryo-EM structure,

82
00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:20.280
rRNAs depicted as colored ribbons make up about half

83
00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:24.300
of the ribosomal complex. Their production is therefore an important

84
00:05:24.340 --> 00:05:28.140
control point in ribosome biogenesis, and more broadly, protein

85
00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:31.520
translation. However, the regulation of

86
00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:35.060
rRNA synthesis across different cell types and in

87
00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:37.760
cancer remains poorly defined.

88
00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:43.460
Within the nucleolus, ribosomal DNA is organized into

89
00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:47.080
hundreds of these nearly identical tandem repeats.

90
00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:51.720
These rDNA loci are transcribed by RNA polymerase I

91
00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:55.120
or Pol I, to initially generate a nascent

92
00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:59.290
47S rRNA. This is a highly active process where

93
00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:03.140
you can have up to 100 Pol I molecules transcribing a single

94
00:06:03.240 --> 00:06:04.469
rDNA locus at a single

95
00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:07.588
time.The

96
00:06:08.288 --> 00:06:11.768
precursor of the nascent RNA is rapidly cleaved into these

97
00:06:11.968 --> 00:06:12.468
mature

98
00:06:13.448 --> 00:06:16.548
rRNAs that are then assembled into the 60S and

99
00:06:16.688 --> 00:06:18.888
40S ribosomal subunits.

100
00:06:20.388 --> 00:06:24.208
Our big picture questions were then, one, how is rRNA

101
00:06:24.228 --> 00:06:27.848
synthesis differentially regulated during normal and malignant

102
00:06:27.898 --> 00:06:31.528
hematopoiesis? And two, is dysregulated rRNA

103
00:06:31.548 --> 00:06:34.128
synthesis a targetable dependency in AML?

104
00:06:35.908 --> 00:06:39.767
To address the first question, we developed a FISH flow assay

105
00:06:39.777 --> 00:06:40.608
to measure

106
00:06:41.748 --> 00:06:45.548
nascent and mature rRNAs at the single cell level

107
00:06:45.628 --> 00:06:47.628
in primary human hematopoietic cells.

108
00:06:48.268 --> 00:06:52.208
We obtained fresh bone marrow aspirates from healthy donors and AML

109
00:06:52.228 --> 00:06:56.128
patients at the hospital of the University of Pennsylvania, isolated

110
00:06:56.148 --> 00:07:00.048
the mononuclear cells, and performed antibody staining to define specific

111
00:07:00.058 --> 00:07:02.208
hematopoietic cell populations.

112
00:07:02.248 --> 00:07:05.668
We then fixed the cells and hybridized them with fluorescent probes

113
00:07:05.728 --> 00:07:09.688
targeting the rRNAs of interest, then measured the probe signal in

114
00:07:09.728 --> 00:07:13.368
each cell by flow cytometry. As shown in these wide field

115
00:07:13.528 --> 00:07:17.428
images, the 47S rRNA probe in purple colocalizes

116
00:07:17.488 --> 00:07:21.428
nicely with Pol1 in green, confirming its

117
00:07:21.438 --> 00:07:22.208
specificity.

118
00:07:23.808 --> 00:07:27.398
And here are our results. On the x-axis are the

119
00:07:27.508 --> 00:07:30.928
different hematopoietic cell types we profiled, and on the

120
00:07:31.008 --> 00:07:34.088
y-axis are the relative rRNA levels.

121
00:07:34.488 --> 00:07:37.948
Nascent 47S rRNA on the left is a

122
00:07:38.008 --> 00:07:41.288
readout of synthesis rate, while mature 18S

123
00:07:42.448 --> 00:07:45.428
on the right is a measurement of ribosome content.

124
00:07:45.768 --> 00:07:49.508
The black dots represent healthy donor cells, while the red

125
00:07:49.828 --> 00:07:51.608
dots represent AML blasts.

126
00:07:52.508 --> 00:07:56.248
Along with normal hematopoiesis, rRNA synthesis and ribosome abundance

127
00:07:56.408 --> 00:07:59.928
decrease with differentiation. For example, along the

128
00:07:59.938 --> 00:08:03.348
erythroid lineage from the MEPs to the

129
00:08:03.408 --> 00:08:07.068
ortho-erythroblasts, both 47S and 18S levels

130
00:08:07.648 --> 00:08:11.628
decline as cells mature, consistent with the shutdown of global

131
00:08:11.728 --> 00:08:15.008
transcription that occurs at later stages of red cell development.

132
00:08:16.708 --> 00:08:16.868
Oh.

133
00:08:18.148 --> 00:08:21.868
And while there is variability among the patient samples depending on the

134
00:08:21.988 --> 00:08:25.908
genotype, treatment status, and aspirate quality, the

135
00:08:25.968 --> 00:08:29.928
overall trend shows that both nascent and mature rRNAs are increased in AML

136
00:08:29.968 --> 00:08:32.757
cells compared to normal hematopoietic cells.

137
00:08:32.928 --> 00:08:36.869
We are still in the process of collecting more samples to obtain more robust

138
00:08:36.879 --> 00:08:40.608
significance, as well as a more representative picture of RNA synthesis across

139
00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:44.488
different molecular subtypes of AML, so stay tuned on that.

140
00:08:45.508 --> 00:08:49.188
To investigate how RNA synthesis is regulated, we then used a

141
00:08:49.208 --> 00:08:53.128
tuneable mouse AML cell line model expressing a HOXA9 estrogen

142
00:08:53.148 --> 00:08:56.358
receptor, or HOXA9ER, fusion protein that is

143
00:08:56.428 --> 00:09:00.218
activated by estradiol. HOXA9 is a master transcription

144
00:09:00.308 --> 00:09:04.137
factor that is overexpressed in over 70% of AMLs and

145
00:09:04.168 --> 00:09:05.678
blocks myeloid differentiation.

146
00:09:06.048 --> 00:09:09.868
In this system, HOXA9 activation maintains a leukemic state,

147
00:09:09.888 --> 00:09:13.208
while inactivation induces differentiation to monocytes.

148
00:09:13.708 --> 00:09:17.678
We found that rRNA synthesis rapidly decreases when

149
00:09:17.688 --> 00:09:21.288
HOXA9 is inactivated and is restored upon

150
00:09:21.308 --> 00:09:25.268
reactivation. And importantly, this occurs before major cell

151
00:09:25.328 --> 00:09:28.828
cycle changes, suggesting that rRNA synthesis is an early

152
00:09:28.888 --> 00:09:31.948
downstream pathway of oncogenic signaling.

153
00:09:33.708 --> 00:09:37.548
We also observed that mRNA and protein expression of

154
00:09:37.568 --> 00:09:41.068
Pol1 subunits are significantly reduced following HOXA9

155
00:09:41.688 --> 00:09:45.508
inactivation. And consistent with this, our single-cell

156
00:09:45.608 --> 00:09:49.388
RNA seq analysis showed that Pol1 expression is elevated in

157
00:09:49.398 --> 00:09:53.288
stem and progenitor cell populations from AML patients

158
00:09:53.328 --> 00:09:57.268
compared to healthy donors. These findings suggest that oncogenes

159
00:09:57.308 --> 00:10:00.948
drive RNA synthesis in part by upregulating the

160
00:10:01.068 --> 00:10:02.668
rRNA transcriptional machinery.

161
00:10:04.608 --> 00:10:08.208
This led us to then ask whether targeting Pol1 could

162
00:10:08.308 --> 00:10:12.288
suppress leukemogenesis. To test this, we generated a degron

163
00:10:12.348 --> 00:10:16.068
system in HOXA9ER AML cells by fusing an

164
00:10:16.188 --> 00:10:19.988
FKBP domain to POLR1A,

165
00:10:20.188 --> 00:10:23.998
which is the catalytic subunit of Pol1, allowing for targeted

166
00:10:23.998 --> 00:10:27.848
degradation of the tagged protein when treated with a small molecule called

167
00:10:27.888 --> 00:10:29.928
dTAG, as shown here in this western blot.

168
00:10:30.708 --> 00:10:34.668
Pol1 degradation led to dose-dependent reductions in rRNA synthesis,

169
00:10:35.028 --> 00:10:38.028
as well as progressive G1 cell cycle arrest.

170
00:10:38.688 --> 00:10:39.528
And interestingly,

171
00:10:40.918 --> 00:10:44.558
persistent Pol1 degradation not only reduced proliferation and

172
00:10:44.588 --> 00:10:48.418
reduced cell viability, but also induced differentiation of

173
00:10:48.448 --> 00:10:52.208
these AML cells, as evidenced by downregulation of a

174
00:10:52.288 --> 00:10:55.968
stem marker c-Kit and upregulation of mature myeloid

175
00:10:56.248 --> 00:11:00.028
markers such as Ly6C, as shown here.

176
00:11:00.608 --> 00:11:04.568
We hypothesized that rRNA hypersynthesis maintains

177
00:11:04.608 --> 00:11:08.508
a stem-like state in AML cells that supports self-renewal

178
00:11:08.588 --> 00:11:12.448
and resistance to pro-apoptotic signals, and that blocking

179
00:11:12.458 --> 00:11:15.848
this pathway would sensitize these cells to

180
00:11:15.928 --> 00:11:19.528
apoptosis-inducing therapies such as venetoclax, a

181
00:11:19.548 --> 00:11:23.428
BCL2 inhibitor that is currently FDA approved for frontline AML therapy.

182
00:11:24.368 --> 00:11:27.938
Notably, HOXA9ER AML cells are TP53 null,

183
00:11:28.448 --> 00:11:31.608
and making them highly resistant to BCL inhibition.

184
00:11:32.248 --> 00:11:36.148
However, Pol1 degradation synergized with venetoclax in suppressing

185
00:11:36.158 --> 00:11:40.008
their growth, as shown by these dose-response curves

186
00:11:40.088 --> 00:11:40.328
here,

187
00:11:41.268 --> 00:11:44.448
where the x-axis represents different concentrations of venetoclax.

188
00:11:44.548 --> 00:11:48.488
The y-axis represents the different degrees of

189
00:11:48.528 --> 00:11:52.388
inhibition, and the different colored curves represent different concentrations of

190
00:11:52.428 --> 00:11:55.988
dTAG. As you can see, increasing concentrations of

191
00:11:56.028 --> 00:11:59.998
dTAG shifted the curves to the left, indicating

192
00:12:00.028 --> 00:12:03.828
that Pol1 degradation potentiates the inhibitory effects

193
00:12:03.948 --> 00:12:07.858
of venetoclax. And here is a 2D synergy plot summarizing that

194
00:12:07.948 --> 00:12:11.752
data. Basically, the redder the color-The stronger

195
00:12:11.872 --> 00:12:15.712
the observed effect is over the expected additive

196
00:12:15.752 --> 00:12:19.192
effect. And a Zipp score of greater than 10

197
00:12:19.252 --> 00:12:22.132
indicates drug synergy. And finally, here

198
00:12:22.292 --> 00:12:26.172
are the percentages of the Nexan 5 positive

199
00:12:26.512 --> 00:12:29.971
dead cells after 40 hours of drug treatment.

200
00:12:30.352 --> 00:12:34.212
So dual Pol1 and BCL2 inhibition has

201
00:12:34.292 --> 00:12:38.232
a synergistically lethal effect on AML cells in vitro.

202
00:12:38.512 --> 00:12:42.092
And what is not shown here is that this synergy

203
00:12:42.152 --> 00:12:44.232
was unique to

204
00:12:46.072 --> 00:12:47.732
dTAG and venetoclax, and not

205
00:12:48.872 --> 00:12:52.652
seen in dTAG and other cytotoxic agents, suggesting

206
00:12:52.712 --> 00:12:56.312
that this is a unique interaction between the rRNA

207
00:12:56.332 --> 00:12:58.532
synthesis and BCL2 pathways.

208
00:12:59.732 --> 00:13:03.492
We also extended these findings to other human AML cell

209
00:13:03.512 --> 00:13:07.352
lines using a small molecule Pol1 inhibitor and observed similar

210
00:13:07.452 --> 00:13:11.212
synergy across the board, regardless of TP53 mutation

211
00:13:11.312 --> 00:13:11.792
status.

212
00:13:13.372 --> 00:13:17.302
So in summary, we've shown that, one, rRNA synthesis and

213
00:13:17.512 --> 00:13:21.352
ribosome content are increased in primary human AML cells.

214
00:13:21.432 --> 00:13:25.402
Two, rRNA synthesis and Pol1 expression are driven by

215
00:13:25.452 --> 00:13:29.272
the oncogenic HOXA9 transcriptional program in myeloid cells.

216
00:13:29.312 --> 00:13:29.812
And three,

217
00:13:31.352 --> 00:13:35.312
Pol1 and BCL2 inhibition synergize to kill AML cells in vitro,

218
00:13:35.612 --> 00:13:39.532
independent of TP53. Together, these findings

219
00:13:40.092 --> 00:13:43.522
identify RNA synthesis as a therapeutically actionable

220
00:13:43.752 --> 00:13:47.302
dependency in AML and suggest a strategy by which we can

221
00:13:47.372 --> 00:13:50.672
overcome venetoclax resistance in refractory or

222
00:13:50.712 --> 00:13:54.122
relapsed disease. We are now

223
00:13:54.172 --> 00:13:57.912
validating this effect in our AML mouse models and

224
00:13:57.952 --> 00:14:01.532
investigating the mechanism of action underlying the

225
00:14:01.612 --> 00:14:02.092
synergy.

226
00:14:04.192 --> 00:14:07.952
With that, I'd like to thank my mentors, colleagues, and funding sources

227
00:14:07.992 --> 00:14:11.882
listed here. Thank you everyone for your attention, and I'm happy to take any

228
00:14:11.912 --> 00:14:13.832
questions at this time.

229
00:14:22.132 --> 00:14:26.012
Hi, very nice work. I wonder a bit between the immature

230
00:14:26.372 --> 00:14:27.352
and the mature

231
00:14:28.272 --> 00:14:30.732
RNA. Do you see differences there?

232
00:14:30.842 --> 00:14:34.732
So let's say you see the good correlation in

233
00:14:34.772 --> 00:14:37.552
the normal cells, but in the AML, maybe the

234
00:14:37.612 --> 00:14:39.452
maturation

235
00:14:39.532 --> 00:14:43.512
differs a bit, or do you see anything

236
00:14:43.572 --> 00:14:46.412
of that, or is this all the same? Once you have high of

237
00:14:47.312 --> 00:14:50.172
one, you have also high of the other one, and there's no

238
00:14:51.112 --> 00:14:52.732
difference in between different cells.

239
00:14:53.272 --> 00:14:57.092
Yeah. So you're asking, do we see a discrepancy in the

240
00:14:57.452 --> 00:14:59.392
nascent versus the mature-

241
00:14:59.432 --> 00:14:59.592
Yeah

242
00:14:59.752 --> 00:15:00.312
... rRNAs, right?

243
00:15:00.342 --> 00:15:00.481
Mm-hmm.

244
00:15:01.092 --> 00:15:04.641
That's a good question. So we generally see that it correlates pretty well.

245
00:15:04.712 --> 00:15:08.152
If you have high nascent RNA levels, you have high

246
00:15:08.572 --> 00:15:10.212
mature RNA levels as well.

247
00:15:11.092 --> 00:15:14.872
But the degree which you see an increase in nascent

248
00:15:14.992 --> 00:15:18.592
RNA is not exactly the same as the increase that you see in the

249
00:15:18.792 --> 00:15:19.952
mature RNA levels.

250
00:15:20.932 --> 00:15:22.292
But we do see a similar trend.

251
00:15:22.772 --> 00:15:23.592
Thank you.

252
00:15:23.632 --> 00:15:24.392
Mm-hmm.

253
00:15:29.892 --> 00:15:32.332
Hi. Klaus Grimosa from the company WMT.

254
00:15:32.992 --> 00:15:34.512
I have more technical question-

255
00:15:34.552 --> 00:15:34.562
Yes

256
00:15:34.632 --> 00:15:35.972
... actually following up to that.

257
00:15:36.572 --> 00:15:40.162
How do you actually determine the rRNA synthesis rate?

